# 🏥 Hospital Emergency Room Dashboard

This project features a **comprehensive and interactive dashboard** that presents vital insights into the performance and efficiency of a hospital's emergency room operations. Designed to support monthly performance reviews, this dashboard aids healthcare administrators, data analysts, and policy makers in monitoring trends, identifying bottlenecks, and enhancing patient care outcomes.

---

## 📌 Overview

The **Hospital Emergency Room Dashboard** provides a month-wise breakdown of patient data, focusing on key metrics such as:

* Total number of patients
* Average wait time
* Patient satisfaction score
* Admission rate
* Gender and age distribution
* Time-to-treatment efficiency
* Referral source analysis

This visual representation is built with clarity and usability in mind, enabling quick decision-making based on real-time data patterns.

---

## 📊 Key Insights (November 2024 Data)

* **Total Patients:** 464
* **Average Wait Time:** 35.19 minutes
* **Patient Satisfaction Score:** 5.09 / 10
* **Patients Attended Within Time:** 61% (Timely) vs. 39% (Delayed)
* **Admission Status:** 50% Admitted, 50% Not Admitted
* **Gender Distribution:** 237 Male, 227 Female
* **Most Affected Age Groups:**

  * 30–44 years: 95 patients
  * 45–59 years: 85 patients
  * 15–29 years: 80 patients
* **Top Referral Sources:**

  * None: 252 (Self-referred or walk-ins)
  * General Practice: 91
  * Orthopedics: 67
  * Physiotherapy, Gastroenterology, and Cardiology (Minor share)

---

## 📈 Dashboard Features

* **Dynamic Year and Month Selector:** Easily switch between 2023 and 2024 to track temporal patterns.
* **Pie Charts & Bar Graphs:** Represent gender distribution, wait-time compliance, age group breakdown, and departmental referrals.
* **Balanced Layout:** Clean segmentation of metrics helps in faster interpretation.
* **Admission Analytics:** Real-time monitoring of admitted vs. non-admitted patient trends.

---

## ✅ Benefits & Use Cases

* **Hospital Administrators:** Optimize staffing, patient flow, and emergency preparedness based on trends.
* **Policy Makers:** Identify age groups and departments needing more resources or attention.
* **Data Analysts:** Use the visualized data to conduct deeper predictive or comparative analysis.
* **Researchers:** Use anonymized data trends for academic publications or healthcare modeling.

